Stage 2 — Data Layer (Offers in Supabase)
Move all offer data from hardcoded JS into Supabase. Enables daily updates without code deploys. Timeline: 3-5 days.

Create offers table in Supabase (see SQL below)
Seed table with all 46+ current offers
Create admin.html — password-protected offer editor
Update app.html to fetch offers from Supabase on load
Keep data.js as offline fallback (last known rates)
Service worker caches offer data with 1-hour TTL

Offers Table SQL

create table public.offers (
  id text primary key,
  name text not null,
  category text not null,  -- bank/invest/cashback/gift/business/earn/mobile/travel/freebie
  reward text not null,
  amount numeric default 0,
  badge text default '',
  effort text default '',
  description text default '',
  code text default '',
  url text not null,
  expected_days integer default 30,
  tips jsonb default '[]',
  warnings jsonb default '[]',
  steps jsonb default '[]',
  is_active boolean default true,
  sort_order integer default 0,
  created_at timestamptz default now(),
  updated_at timestamptz default now()
);

alter table public.offers enable row level security;
create policy "Public read" on public.offers for select using (true);
-- Only service role (admin panel) can insert/update/delete

Stage 3 — App Architecture Refactor
Split the single 3,700-line file into maintainable modules. Timeline: 5-7 days.

File
Contents

app.html
Shell only — head, nav, section containers, script tags. Under 200 lines.

app.css
All CSS — variables, components, animations. Cached separately.

app.js
All JavaScript — state, renders, event handlers, auth, sync.

data.js
Offline fallback offers data — static snapshot, auto-generated from Supabase.

admin.html
Password-protected offer editor — reads/writes Supabase offers table.

Render optimisation in app.js:

Replace renderAll() with targeted renders per section
Add dirty flag system: markDirty("offers"), markDirty("profile") etc.
Single tick() function renders only dirty sections on next animation frame
Battle table and stacking guides render once on load only

Stage 4 — Native App Feel
Make the app feel like iOS/Android. Timeline: 3-4 days.

Page transitions — slide animations between tabs (CSS transforms, not reloads)
Pull-to-refresh on offers tab
Haptic feedback on every meaningful interaction (navigator.vibrate)
Bottom sheet modals — auth, pending payout popup, all use sheet pattern
No visible scrollbars (-webkit-scrollbar: none)
Safe area insets on all fixed elements (env(safe-area-inset-bottom))
Proper tap highlight removal (-webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent)
Loading states for every async operation

Stage 5 — Growth Features
Features that drive user acquisition and retention. Timeline: ongoing.

Real-time leaderboard from Supabase progress table
Push notifications via Railway (Web Push API + VAPID keys)
"What to do next" smart recommendation engine
Amazon affiliate links (amazon.co.uk affiliate programme)
Jam Doughnut / Tillo live rates API (when partnership approved)
Weekly email digest sent via Brevo automation
Referral system — users invite friends, both get bonus XP

4. Agent Rules & Working Protocol

Every AI agent or developer working on this project MUST follow these rules without exception.

4.1 Before Starting Any Task

Read this entire document first
Check the Progress Log (Section 6) to understand what has already been done
Read the current state of the file(s) you will be modifying
Identify which Known Issues (Section 2) your task relates to
Write your test plan before writing any code

RULE: Never Assume, Always Read

Do not assume you know what the current code looks like. Always read the actual file before editing. The codebase changes frequently and your training data will be stale.

4.2 Constraints — Never Violate These

NO build step — the app must deploy by drag-and-drop to GitHub Pages. No webpack, Vite, npm build, or compilation required.
NO framework — no React, Vue, Angular, or Svelte. Vanilla JS only.
NO secrets in frontend code — API keys, tokens, passwords belong in Railway Variables or Supabase environment only.
NO breaking the live site — test locally first. If it breaks locally it will break in production.
NO sequential await loops for Supabase — always batch upserts.
NO direct writes to auth.users — always use supabase.auth methods.
ALWAYS keep localStorage as primary storage — Supabase is the sync layer, not the source of truth on-device.
ALWAYS test on mobile viewport (375px width minimum) before marking complete.

4.3 Coding Standards

JavaScript
Use const by default, let when reassignment is needed, never var
Async functions must handle errors with try/catch — never let promises fail silently
All Supabase calls must have timeout handling
No inline event handlers in HTML (onclick="...") — use addEventListener in JS
Functions must be single-purpose and under 40 lines — extract if longer
Name functions clearly: renderOffers(), pushProgress(), handleSignup()

CSS
Use CSS custom properties (variables) for all colours, radii, shadows
Mobile-first: base styles for mobile, media queries for desktop
Minimum touch target size: 44x44px (Apple HIG standard)
Minimum font size: 13px for body, 11px absolute minimum for labels
Never use px for font sizes alone — use rem or ensure base is set

TypeScript (Future)
When the project migrates to TypeScript (Stage 3+), these rules apply:
Strict mode enabled: "strict": true in tsconfig.json
No any types — use unknown and type guards
All Supabase responses typed using generated types (supabase gen types typescript)
Zod for runtime validation of API responses

4.4 Git & Deployment Rules

Never commit secrets — use .gitignore and Railway Variables
Commit messages: "feat: add password reset flow" / "fix: batch Supabase upsert" / "docs: update progress log"
One feature per commit — do not bundle unrelated changes
GitHub Pages deploys automatically on push to main — verify the live site after every push
Railway deploys automatically on push to the bot repo — check /health after every deploy
Keep requirements.txt pinned: requests==2.31.0, schedule==1.2.0, flask, flask-cors

Deployment Checklist (run before every push)

1. JS syntax check: node --input-type=module (check for errors)
2. Test on mobile viewport (375px)
3. Test auth flow (signup, login, sync)
4. Check /health endpoint after Railway deploy
5. Hard refresh on live site (Ctrl+Shift+R) to clear SW cache
6. Update Progress Log in this document

5. Testing Protocol

All agents must run the full test suite before marking any task complete. Tests are described below by category.

5.1 Test Categories

Category
What It Tests
Tool

Unit
Individual functions in isolation
Jest (when TypeScript migrated)

Integration
Supabase auth, sync, and API calls
